{"id":"2208.08971","submitter":"Gabriel Coutinho","authors":"Gabriel Coutinho, Pedro Ferreira Baptista, Chris Godsil, Thom\\'as Jung\n  Spier, Reinhard Werner","title":"Irrational quantum walks","comments":"22 pages, 5 figures. Code to test pretty good state transfer is\n  available upon request","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph math-ph math.CO math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The adjacency matrix of a graph G is the Hamiltonian for a continuous-time\nquantum walk on the vertices of G. Although the entries of the adjacency matrix\nare integers, its eigenvalues are generally irrational and, because of this,\nthe behaviour of the walk is typically not periodic. In consequence we can\nusually only compute numerical approximations to parameters of the walk. In\nthis paper, we develop theory to exactly study any quantum walk generated by an\nintegral Hamiltonian. As a result, we provide exact methods to compute the\naverage of the mixing matrices, and to decide whether pretty good (or almost)\nperfect state transfer occurs in a given graph. We also use our methods to\nstudy geometric properties of beautiful curves arising from entries of the\nquantum walk matrix, and discuss possible applications of these results.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 18 Aug 2022 17:21:47 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-08-19"}
